entry.title: [color] Add UserColorSource param to the ColorProviderKey
entry.content:
This CL introduces the UserColorSource enum to the key, replacing

the previous is_grayscale param in the process.



The enum defines baseline, grayscale and accent color sources. These

options define how the color pipeline selects the input color for the

generation of sys color tokens. These options are intended to be

mutually exclusive.



This CL also sets the default source to baseline on windows platforms.

Follow up CLs will populate the user_color on Windows' NativeTheme

instance from the AccentColorObserver. However on Windows we do not

want to express this accent color unless the user has explicitly

opted to do so for their browser. This is in contrast to ChromeOS

where we expect the accent color to be expressed in the absence of

any overrides by the browser.

entry.content:
When opening an archive with encrypted metadata, unrar expects to have a

password. If one is not provided, it will throw an exception. While

code. Instead this CL provides a dummy password (the letter x) when

entry.title: Make standards-track pseudo-elements override style attributes in UA shadow DOM.
entry.content:
This makes pseudo-elements representing elements in user-agent shadow

DOM (via Element::ShadowPseudoId()) whose names do not begin with

-webkit- or -internal- override style attributes in the user-agent

shadow DOM. This matches developer expectations and makes sense given

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-cascade-5/#cascade-context since the

pseudo-elements are in an outer context.



The only such pseudo-elements that exist today are the experimental

::details-content and ::details-summary pseudo-elements. (See the

DCHECK() in Element::SetShadowPseudoId().)



TODO(https://crbug.com/1478230): Devtools does not currently show the

correct cascading order since it assumes that style attributes always

win. We should fix this before shipping this code.

entry.title: exo: Send enter/leave events only to mapped surfaces
entry.content:
Sending enter events before a surface is mapped - i.e. has a buffer

attached[1][2] - is a implicit protocol violation[3]. The current

behavior notably causes the SDL2 Wayland backend to not enter fullscreen

mode, essentially breaking games.



Thus ensure to only send the events if the surface already is mapped or

when it gets mapped.



Note: One reason to send enter events before mapping a surface is to

allow clients to render the first frame with the correct buffer scale and transform values. For that reason version 6 of the core protocol

introduced `wl_surface.preferred_buffer_scale` and

`wl_surface.preferred_buffer_transform`, allowing compositors to send

clients hints whenever they see fit.



[1]: long version:

https://wayland.app/protocols/wayland#wl_surface:request:attach

[2]: more explicit version for subsurfaces, applies to other surfaces as

well though:

https://wayland.app/protocols/wayland#wl_subsurface

Notably: "A sub-surface becomes mapped, when a non-NULL wl_buffer is

applied and the parent surface is mapped. The order of which one happens

first is irrelevant. A sub-surface is hidden if the parent becomes

hidden, or if a NULL wl_buffer is applied. These rules apply recursively

through the tree of surfaces."

[3]: https://wayland.app/protocols/wayland#wl_surface:event:enter

Notably: "Note that a surface may be overlapping with zero or more

outputs."

entry.title: Start the init thread *before* NativeInit()
entry.content:
Initializing Android Cronet from the native Cronet API happens through

EnsureInitialized(), which calls NativeInit() and *then* starts the

Java Cronet init thread. This is inconsistent with how Cronet is

initialized when using Cronet from the Java API: in this case,

CronetLibraryLoader.ensureInitialized() starts the init thread first,

and *then* calls the Cronet JNI OnLoad routine which calls

NativeInit().



This inconsistency can cause headaches when changing Cronet

initialization code, especially if these threads have to wait on each

other. We resolve the inconsistency by changing the native entry point

(EnsureInitialized()) to run the steps in the same order as the Java

entry point (CronetLibraryLoader.ensureInitialized()).



This change might also improve native initialization performance by

improving parallelism with the init thread.



Change-Id: Id46503a721cd58e636950ab765dcc1667afb7915

entry.title: Clamp non-finite inputs to legacy color formats at parse time
entry.content:
https://github.com/web-platform-tests/interop/issues/369



All legacy colors parse to `rgb( , , )` or `rgba( , , , )` with integers

in the range [0, 255] for the color channels and [0, 1] for alpha. Since

the channels are bounded, non finite inputs should resolve to the upper

bound for "infinity" and the lower bound for "-infinity" and "NaN".



The parser was also previously allowing unbounded alpha at parse time.

Alpha is also a bounded channel and non-finite inputs should be clamped

to [0, 1]. This behavior was previously untested, but is tested here

in new tests added to color-valid-rgb.html.

entry.title: [css-nesting-ident] Handle restarts in StyleSheetHandler
entry.content:
Since declarations that fail to parse are now retried as nested style

rules, we can end up with CSSParserObserver events that claim that we

both have a failed declaration and a valid style rule at the same

offset. This is technically correct, but StyleSheetHandler needs a

better interpretation of this to stay in a consistent state.



In short, we now remove the CSSPropertySourceData produced by

the conflicting ObserveProperty event if a valid style rule is

seen in the same offset. This means that:



- Token sequences that fail as declarations, but pass as

style rules will appear as style rules.

- Token sequences that fail as declarations, and that also fail

as style rules will will appear as declarations (like before).



For token sequences that pass as declarations, there is of course

no difference, because we never retry parsing as style rules for

those sequences.

entry.title: [bookmarks] Carry over local UUIDs when uploading all local bookmarks
entry.content:
When the destination BookmarkModel doesn't contain a colliding UUID, it

is best to reuse the local bookmark's original UUID when copying it to

the account BookmarkModel instance.



This makes it less likely that, in the long run, users run into

undesired bookmark duplicates, as UUID-based matching is very robust.



As a minor side change, the hashing function used for semantic-based

matching is improved, hoping that it improves the performance for

worst-case scenarios where many sibling nodes shared the same title.

entry.title: [Tab Switcher] Mark tab as hidden after showing
entry.content:
Call Tab#hide() for the current tab when finished showing the Tab

Switcher, including animations and thumbnail capture. This marks the

Tab and its WebContents as hidden and should reduce extra work such as

animations. Because the tab is selected it will still have a foreground

renderer binding which should prevent any negative side-effect.

Clicking the selected tab or pressing back invokes setIndex which will

undo the side-effect of the hide [1].



This action will be cancelled if exiting the tab switcher before the

thumbnail is captured.

sources the user could not choose from are NOT counted as 0.

* An extension API is invoked to not offer tabs/windows/screens.

* An enterprise policy is used to limit sharing.

entry.title: Condition language-dependent parsing on AutofillPageLanguageDetection.
entry.content:
FormStructure::current_page_language_ has two uses:

- To attach it to the upload request (for the metadata pipeline).

- To use language-dependent regexes when AutofillParsingPatternProvider

is enabled.

It is determined using some translate API.



Setting a form structure's language happens at multiple places, but most

notably right before parsing a form on page load. At this point, the

page language might or might not have been by translate yet. If it has

been determined, that page language is used for local heuristics when

pattern provider is enabled, even if AutofillPageLanguageDetection is

disabled.



At the moment, AutofillPageLanguageDetection only controls if an

additional local heuristics call happens after the page language was

determined (using a LanguageDetectionObserver in AutofillManager).



This CL changes the parsing logic slightly to condition the use of

current_page_language_ on AutofillPageLanguageDetection. This only has

an effect when AutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled but

AutofillPageLanguageDetection is disabled. This allows rolling out

pattern provider without page language detection (by not providing a

page language, regexes of all languages are used).



The metadata pipeline is unaffected by this change. This logic was

added long before pattern provider and AutofillPageLanguageDetection in

~2018 by http://crrev.com/c/1358634.

entry.title: ui-controls: Remove set_toplevel_bounds request
entry.content:
Many TabDragging tests pass require control over browser windows'

bounds, which isn't possible on Wayland without aura-shell. Thus, a

set_toplevel_bounds request was added to ui-controls to help with making

these tests pass on Linux ozone/wayland.



However, it turned out that implementing this request in Weston is quite

complicated. It's a lot easier to take a different approach: use

emulated mouse events to resizes and move the browser windows like a

real user would do. This is being implemented in

https://crrev.com/c/4738688, and it seems to work great.



Thus, we don't need the set_toplevel_bounds request after all, and can

remove it.

entry.title: [css-nesting-ident] Check for property validity earlier
entry.content:
When attempting to parse a declaration, we do things in the following

order, ignoring whitespace:



1. Consume an ident. (Normally a property name).

2. Consume a semicolon.

3. Consume the value tokens. This means scanning until the first

top-level semicolon. Actual value-parsing happens later.

4. Check if the ident from (1) is a valid property.

5. Parse the value.



The problem is that we're checking for property validity (4) *after*

consuming the value tokens (3). This is bad for nested contexts,

because (3) is potentially a lot of wasted tokenization work if

we're going to restart the stream due to a property being invalid (4).



Therefore, this CL refactors ConsumeDeclaration such that

ConsumeValue generally happens *after* we check for property

validity.



On my machine, with CSSNestingIdent set to status:stable,

the included performance test takes around 13ms with the optimization

and 495ms without the optimization. The important part here is that

there's a clear signal in the case of a regression.



The style perftest (style_perftest.cc) seems neutral for this CL.
